{"parse":{"title":"Threshold population","pageid":5696235,"revid":848116436,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Microeconomics\" title=\"Microeconomics\">microeconomics</a>, a <b>threshold population</b> is the minimum number of people needed for a <a href=\"/wiki/Service_(economics)\" title=\"Service (economics)\">service</a> to be worthwhile.\n</p><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Geography\" title=\"Geography\">geography</a>, a threshold population is the minimum number of people necessary before a particular <a href=\"/wiki/Good_(economics)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Good (economics)\">good</a> or service can be provided in an area. The concept is equivalent to the \"range\" in <a href=\"/wiki/Central_place_theory\" title=\"Central place theory\">central place theory</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Retailing\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Retailing\">retailing</a>, which delineates the <a href=\"/wiki/Market_(economics)\" title=\"Market (economics)\">market</a> area of a central place for a particular good or service, and is dependent on the <a href=\"/wiki/Population_density\" title=\"Population density\">spatial distribution</a> of population and the willingness of <a href=\"/wiki/Consumer\" title=\"Consumer\">consumers</a> to travel a given distance to purchase particular goods or services.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Typically a low-order shop (such as a grocer or newsagent) may require only 800 or so customers, whereas a higher-order store such as Marks and Spencer or Waitrose may need a threshold of 70,000 to be profitable, and a university may need 350,000 to be viable.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Thresholds may also be linked to the spending power of customers; this is most obvious in periodic markets in poor countries, where wages are so low that people can buy the goods or services only once in a while.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Threshold_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Goodall, B. (1987) The Penguin Dictionary of Human Geography. London: Penguin.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.tiscali.co.uk/reference/encyclopaedia/hutchinson/m0034885.html\">Tiscali encyclopedia</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20071012030055/http://www.tiscali.co.uk/reference/encyclopaedia/hutchinson/m0034885.html\">Archived</a> 2007-10-12 at the <a href=\"/wiki/Wayback_Machine\" title=\"Wayback Machine\">Wayback Machine</a>.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Usdollar100front.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Usdollar100front.jpg/40px-Usdollar100front.jpg\" width=\"40\" height=\"17\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Usdollar100front.jpg/60px-Usdollar100front.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Usdollar100front.jpg/80px-Usdollar100front.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"5532\" data-file-height=\"2325\" /></a></td><td><i>This article related to <a href=\"/wiki/Microeconomics\" title=\"Microeconomics